WEBVTT

1
00:00:47.101 --> 00:00:49.092
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

2
00:00:49.501 --> 00:00:51.378
[WOMAN CACKLING]

3
00:00:51.541 --> 00:00:53.179
FRED:
Come on.

4
00:00:57.101 --> 00:00:58.853
Split up.

5
00:01:02.421 --> 00:01:04.981
SHAGGY: Hey, come on, Scoob.
SCOOBY: I'm right behind you, Shaggy.

6
00:01:05.141 --> 00:01:07.132
[SHAGGY SCREAMS]

7
00:01:07.661 --> 00:01:09.731
Change of plans.

8
00:01:13.421 --> 00:01:15.412
WOMAN:
Stay out.

9
00:01:15.581 --> 00:01:17.572
[GRUNTING]

10
00:01:18.501 --> 00:01:21.538
Time to unmask the person
behind this mystery.

11
00:01:23.021 --> 00:01:25.694
- It's you?
- What?

12
00:01:25.861 --> 00:01:28.614
Like, it can't be.

13
00:01:38.781 --> 00:01:41.818
MAN: Remember, people, just because
this is the last day of class...

14
00:01:42.021 --> 00:01:43.977
...doesn't mean
this test doesn't count.

15
00:01:47.781 --> 00:01:48.975
Huh?

16
00:01:52.621 --> 00:01:54.293
No.

17
00:02:06.261 --> 00:02:07.376
Yes.

18
00:02:08.541 --> 00:02:10.611
Cowabunga.

19
00:02:14.941 --> 00:02:16.340
- Hot dog.
- Hot dog.

20
00:02:17.781 --> 00:02:19.658
GIRL 1:
Let's dance.

21
00:02:21.661 --> 00:02:23.413
Yeah.

22
00:02:35.341 --> 00:02:36.376
[GIRL 2 WHISTLES]

23
00:02:37.021 --> 00:02:40.491
Uh, guys, what are you doing?

24
00:02:40.701 --> 00:02:42.896
I know you're excited
the school year's over...

25
00:02:43.061 --> 00:02:45.017
...but our seasonal employment
awaits.

26
00:02:45.221 --> 00:02:48.497
Already? Like, I didn't even have time
to get a tan.

27
00:02:48.661 --> 00:02:50.333
- Yeah.
- Come on.

28
00:02:55.181 --> 00:02:57.172
[CHEERING]

29
00:03:00.941 --> 00:03:03.580
Well, it sure is lucky
that Daphne's uncle...

30
00:03:03.741 --> 00:03:06.255
...is opening his new country club
this summer, hey, V?

31
00:03:06.421 --> 00:03:09.413
Indeed. Without these summer jobs,
we'd never able to pay back...

32
00:03:09.581 --> 00:03:12.049
...Old Man Frickert
for the damage we did to his barn.

33
00:03:12.581 --> 00:03:14.537
Say cheese.

34
00:03:14.701 --> 00:03:15.975
[GIGGLES]

35
00:03:16.141 --> 00:03:18.735
- What is he...?
- Oh, Scoob's got a new hobby.

36
00:03:18.901 --> 00:03:20.300
Scrapbooking.

37
00:03:20.461 --> 00:03:23.578
- What happened to gardening?
- It didn't work out.

38
00:03:23.741 --> 00:03:26.778
Everything he planted,
he'd just dig right up.

39
00:03:28.181 --> 00:03:29.580
VELMA:
Hm.

40
00:03:29.981 --> 00:03:33.610
Daphne said we should hit the road
right after school.

41
00:03:33.781 --> 00:03:35.897
Any sign of her or Fred?

42
00:03:36.061 --> 00:03:37.540
Uh-uh.

43
00:03:38.581 --> 00:03:39.775
[VELMA GASPS]

44
00:03:39.941 --> 00:03:42.011
- Like, huh?
VELMA: Jinkies.

45
00:03:42.221 --> 00:03:43.620
Ooh.

46
00:03:44.341 --> 00:03:46.013
Perfect.

47
00:03:48.701 --> 00:03:52.216
Well? I for one think we deserve
an explanation.

48
00:03:52.381 --> 00:03:54.019
- Yeah.
- Yes.

49
00:03:54.221 --> 00:03:58.692
There's always been an undeniable
chemistry between you two, but...

50
00:03:58.861 --> 00:04:02.410
When did the transformative reaction
finally occur?

51
00:04:03.421 --> 00:04:05.810
I guess it started that night
at Old Man Frickert's.

52
00:04:05.981 --> 00:04:07.778
Yeah. Remember, Velma?

53
00:04:07.941 --> 00:04:11.411
<i>We followed the trail of the vengeful</i>
<i>scarecrow up into the hayloft.</i>

54
00:04:11.581 --> 00:04:13.412
This is impossible.

55
00:04:13.581 --> 00:04:16.015
We'll never find anything in here.

56
00:04:16.381 --> 00:04:18.941
Yes, if I wasn't so pun averse...

57
00:04:19.101 --> 00:04:22.138
...I might even say it's like looking
for a needle in a haystack.

58
00:04:22.301 --> 00:04:23.495
[MAN ROARS]

59
00:04:23.661 --> 00:04:25.492
MAN:
Didn't scare you, did I?

60
00:04:25.701 --> 00:04:27.100
[VELMA & DAPHNE SCREAMING]

61
00:04:27.261 --> 00:04:28.660
Daphne.

62
00:04:31.221 --> 00:04:32.813
Are you okay?

63
00:04:33.581 --> 00:04:35.458
I am now.

64
00:04:37.261 --> 00:04:39.456
SHAGGY: Like, run!
- What is it, Shaggy?

65
00:04:39.621 --> 00:04:42.818
- This one's gonna be a real barn burner.
FRED: Shaggy.

66
00:04:43.381 --> 00:04:45.053
Look out!

67
00:04:47.501 --> 00:04:50.061
DAPHNE: And thus,
we're stuck paying for a new barn.

68
00:04:50.221 --> 00:04:52.291
Again, just for the record...

69
00:04:52.461 --> 00:04:54.929
...nowhere on those bales of hay
did it say flammable.

70
00:04:55.101 --> 00:04:57.569
SCOOBY: Yeah.
- Anyway, that was also the night...

71
00:04:57.741 --> 00:05:00.733
...that Fred and I realized
we were just meant to be.

72
00:05:04.021 --> 00:05:06.012
It's a lovely story.

73
00:05:06.181 --> 00:05:09.014
But I do feel obligated
to raise one concern.

74
00:05:09.181 --> 00:05:11.251
Whenever there's a shift
in a relationship...

75
00:05:11.421 --> 00:05:14.015
...between two individuals
within a group...

76
00:05:14.181 --> 00:05:17.730
...it inevitably has repercussions
on the group as a whole.

77
00:05:18.981 --> 00:05:21.700
SHAGGY:
Oh, Velma, don't worry about that.

78
00:05:21.861 --> 00:05:24.580
We're all way too mature
to let that happen.

79
00:05:24.741 --> 00:05:27.619
- Right, Scoob?
- I know I am.

80
00:05:29.061 --> 00:05:30.460
Punch buggy white.

81
00:05:30.621 --> 00:05:33.931
Ouch. Oh, good one, Scoob.

82
00:05:34.101 --> 00:05:37.332
But it's a shame you didn't notice
the punch buggy green.

83
00:05:37.501 --> 00:05:38.854
Ow!

84
00:05:40.701 --> 00:05:42.259
[SHAGGY & SCOOBY GRUNTING]

85
00:05:42.421 --> 00:05:44.810
- All right.
- You know what? That is it. I've had it.

86
00:05:44.981 --> 00:05:48.257
You know, I will turn this van around.

87
00:05:49.621 --> 00:05:51.691
- Do I have to come back there?
DAPHNE: Scooby-Doo...

88
00:05:51.861 --> 00:05:54.136
...get your tail out of my face.

89
00:05:55.341 --> 00:05:58.014
DAPHNE: Fred, where are those
directions I sent you to print out?

90
00:05:58.221 --> 00:06:01.850
Don't worry, we're not lost.

91
00:06:07.221 --> 00:06:10.611
DAPHNE: Hm. This sure doesn't look
like my uncle's country club.

92
00:06:11.701 --> 00:06:14.454
Oh. Hey, look. It's the <i>S.S. Daphne.</i>

93
00:06:15.461 --> 00:06:17.292
DAPHNE:
Ha, ha.

94
00:06:17.461 --> 00:06:19.895
Oh, look. Try stopping there, sweetie.

95
00:06:20.101 --> 00:06:22.217
FRED:
Whatever you say, dear.

96
00:06:30.701 --> 00:06:32.931
VELMA:
Oh, how quaint.

97
00:06:42.541 --> 00:06:43.530
Hm.

98
00:06:43.701 --> 00:06:45.612
Hello?

99
00:06:45.821 --> 00:06:47.937
Anybody home?

100
00:06:48.141 --> 00:06:51.292
Like, yikes. Maybe we ought to just find
our own way...

101
00:06:51.461 --> 00:06:53.497
...to your uncle's country club.

102
00:06:54.701 --> 00:06:55.690
Zoinks!

103
00:06:55.861 --> 00:06:57.010
Country club?

104
00:06:57.181 --> 00:07:00.139
You're going to the country club?

105
00:07:00.301 --> 00:07:02.132
Yes, we have summer jobs there.

106
00:07:02.341 --> 00:07:06.459
No, you must turn back.
You must leave while you still can.

107
00:07:06.621 --> 00:07:10.455
- Leave? Why would we wanna leave?
- They were fools to build there.

108
00:07:10.621 --> 00:07:11.736
I tried to warn them...

109
00:07:11.901 --> 00:07:14.210
...but they thought
I was just some crazy hag.

110
00:07:14.381 --> 00:07:16.576
You? Heh. No.

111
00:07:16.781 --> 00:07:20.820
But mark my words,
the lake monster will return.

112
00:07:21.021 --> 00:07:24.855
The lake monster will return.

113
00:07:25.821 --> 00:07:27.812
[WHIMPERING]

114
00:07:28.501 --> 00:07:30.492
- Did you get directions?
- Uh...

115
00:07:30.661 --> 00:07:32.492
- Not exactly.
SHAGGY: Oh, yes, we did.

116
00:07:32.701 --> 00:07:35.659
Make a U-turn
and head straight back to Coolsville.

117
00:07:35.861 --> 00:07:39.137
There's a monster at the lake, guys.
A monster.

118
00:07:39.341 --> 00:07:41.411
- A monster?
- Mm-hm.

119
00:07:41.621 --> 00:07:44.579
Would you be referring
to the lake monster of Erie Pointe?

120
00:07:45.141 --> 00:07:47.496
You know, I didn't catch his name.

121
00:07:47.661 --> 00:07:50.653
- All I heard was "monster."
VELMA: No, look.

122
00:07:52.341 --> 00:07:55.777
It says here for hundreds of years
there have been sightings...

123
00:07:55.941 --> 00:07:59.570
...of hideous creatures
said to live at the bottom of the lake.

124
00:07:59.781 --> 00:08:03.296
I get it, it's one of those things
like Bigfoot or the Loch Ness monster.

125
00:08:03.501 --> 00:08:06.493
Oh, no, it's worse than we thought.

126
00:08:06.661 --> 00:08:09.653
No, Shaggy, I think what Fred means
is that it's just a legend.

127
00:08:09.821 --> 00:08:13.052
You know, lots of small towns
make them up. They're good for tourism.

128
00:08:13.501 --> 00:08:16.538
Oh. Oh, sure, you know,
come for the scenery...

129
00:08:16.701 --> 00:08:19.010
...stay for the certain death.

130
00:08:19.621 --> 00:08:20.610
[THUD]

131
00:08:20.781 --> 00:08:23.341
Come on, guys. Let's just get going
or we're gonna be late.

132
00:08:25.421 --> 00:08:27.093
Uh, Fred?

133
00:08:27.741 --> 00:08:30.858
- We still don't know how to get there.
- Mm-hm.

134
00:08:31.021 --> 00:08:35.139
Actually, yes, we do.

135
00:08:35.461 --> 00:08:36.655
[SHAGGY SIGHS]

136
00:08:36.821 --> 00:08:38.220
- No.
- Yes.

137
00:08:50.021 --> 00:08:51.454
FRED:
Pretty swank, Daph.

138
00:08:51.621 --> 00:08:55.455
DAPHNE: Yeah, looks like my uncle
really outdid himself this time.

139
00:08:59.301 --> 00:09:01.019
Thanks, Shaggy.

140
00:09:01.541 --> 00:09:02.530
[LAUGHS]

141
00:09:02.701 --> 00:09:06.535
- Is that my favorite niece?
- Uncle Thorny.

142
00:09:08.141 --> 00:09:09.369
Wow.

143
00:09:10.741 --> 00:09:12.697
Thank you again, uncle.

144
00:09:12.861 --> 00:09:15.659
I don't know what we would've done
without these summer jobs.

145
00:09:15.821 --> 00:09:18.619
Yeah. And, again, just for the record...

146
00:09:18.781 --> 00:09:21.614
...it's a well-known fact
that scarecrows are afraid of fire...

147
00:09:21.781 --> 00:09:22.770
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

148
00:09:22.941 --> 00:09:25.853
Gang, I'd like you to meet
Thorton Blake IV.

149
00:09:26.021 --> 00:09:27.340
Fifth, actually.

150
00:09:27.501 --> 00:09:29.173
Uncle Thorny, this is the gang.

151
00:09:29.381 --> 00:09:30.370
This is Shaggy.

152
00:09:30.541 --> 00:09:31.656
- Hi.
- Hi.

153
00:09:31.821 --> 00:09:33.413
- Fred.
- Oh.

154
00:09:33.861 --> 00:09:35.214
DAPHNE: Velma.
- Pleasure.

155
00:09:35.381 --> 00:09:36.734
- And...
SCOOBY: Scooby-Doo.

156
00:09:36.901 --> 00:09:38.414
Nice to meet you, Uncle Thorny.

157
00:09:38.581 --> 00:09:40.378
Smile.

158
00:09:40.541 --> 00:09:42.133
[SCOOBY GIGGLES]

159
00:09:42.821 --> 00:09:45.938
Well, I'm sure glad to have you all
on board this summer.

160
00:09:46.141 --> 00:09:50.373
Grab your stuff, get settled,
and park that thing in the back.

161
00:09:50.541 --> 00:09:53.578
Oh. You're gonna need
to get a good night's sleep.

162
00:09:53.741 --> 00:09:57.256
Your shifts start at 6 a.m. sharp.

163
00:09:58.461 --> 00:10:00.099
There's a 6 a. m?

164
00:10:01.101 --> 00:10:02.090
[SIGHS]

165
00:10:03.861 --> 00:10:06.580
And that one. It's my makeup.

166
00:10:09.621 --> 00:10:11.293
[SHAGGY GRUNTING]

167
00:10:11.461 --> 00:10:14.737
- Shaggy, need a hand?
- No, thanks, Fred. I got it.

168
00:10:14.901 --> 00:10:17.495
It just takes a little elbow grease.

169
00:10:17.661 --> 00:10:19.140
[GASPING]

170
00:10:19.301 --> 00:10:20.529
Shaggy.

171
00:10:23.421 --> 00:10:27.494
Shaggy, are you all right?

172
00:10:28.181 --> 00:10:30.536
Like, I am now.

173
00:10:31.421 --> 00:10:32.649
Shaggy.

174
00:10:33.381 --> 00:10:35.099
Yes, Velma?

175
00:10:35.301 --> 00:10:39.135
I don't know how much longer
I can hold you.

176
00:10:50.421 --> 00:10:52.377
- Hey, Scoob?
- Huh?

177
00:10:53.701 --> 00:10:56.374
- Can I talk to you man-to-man?
- Uh...

178
00:10:56.541 --> 00:10:58.497
Sort of.

179
00:10:58.701 --> 00:11:01.932
I think I might have just had
a hayloft moment with Velma.

180
00:11:03.101 --> 00:11:05.410
Do you think it's possible that...?

181
00:11:05.581 --> 00:11:11.213
I don't know,
that she and I are meant to be?

182
00:11:12.021 --> 00:11:14.057
[LAUGHING]

183
00:11:17.261 --> 00:11:19.855
Yeah. Thanks for the support, pal.

184
00:11:20.061 --> 00:11:22.655
I'll remember this come flea season.

185
00:11:24.981 --> 00:11:26.972
[PUFFING]

186
00:11:29.901 --> 00:11:31.892
[CONTINUES LAUGHING]

187
00:11:37.301 --> 00:11:38.700
[TREE BRANCHES RUSTLE]

188
00:11:39.501 --> 00:11:42.493
Getting much better distance
on those woods, sir.

189
00:11:43.181 --> 00:11:48.016
Hey, Fred,
can I talk to you man-to-man?

190
00:11:48.661 --> 00:11:50.253
Sort of.

191
00:11:50.821 --> 00:11:55.178
Well, you and Daphne,
is that something you recommend?

192
00:11:55.341 --> 00:11:56.899
What do you mean?

193
00:11:57.061 --> 00:11:59.529
Well, you know, going from having...

194
00:11:59.701 --> 00:12:03.216
...you know, a girl friend
to a girlfriend.

195
00:12:03.381 --> 00:12:07.454
Heh, heh. I don't know if I'd really
call Daphne my girlfriend, Shags.

196
00:12:07.621 --> 00:12:10.055
You know, it's more casual than that.
We're just, um...

197
00:12:10.221 --> 00:12:12.451
- We're hanging out.
- Hanging out?

198
00:12:12.621 --> 00:12:15.260
No, Fred is totally my boyfriend.

199
00:12:15.421 --> 00:12:16.649
Really?

200
00:12:16.821 --> 00:12:19.779
I always thought football players
liked to, well...

201
00:12:19.941 --> 00:12:21.852
...play the field.
- Pfft.

202
00:12:22.021 --> 00:12:26.890
Me too. I never thought Fred would
be the relationship type, but he totally is.

203
00:12:27.101 --> 00:12:28.693
I'm just not the relationship type.

204
00:12:28.861 --> 00:12:31.978
I'm a football player,
we like to, uh, play the field.

205
00:12:32.141 --> 00:12:33.893
Anyhow, it's summer, Shaggy.

206
00:12:34.061 --> 00:12:36.814
Oh, yeah, summer. Totally.

207
00:12:37.541 --> 00:12:41.534
Because who'd want a girlfriend
during daylight-savings time?

208
00:12:42.581 --> 00:12:44.173
Good guess, but what I'm saying...

209
00:12:44.341 --> 00:12:47.378
...is summer's a time you just wanna
have fun. Not get so serious.

210
00:12:47.541 --> 00:12:49.771
Daphne's cool,
she feels the same way.

211
00:12:49.941 --> 00:12:52.057
It's totally getting serious.

212
00:12:52.221 --> 00:12:54.337
Fred's cool, he feels the same way.

213
00:12:54.501 --> 00:12:58.540
Well, it certainly sounds
like you two are perfectly in sync.

214
00:12:58.701 --> 00:12:59.736
Yeah.

215
00:12:59.901 --> 00:13:01.812
- Exactly.
- Exactly.

216
00:13:02.021 --> 00:13:04.012
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

217
00:13:05.261 --> 00:13:07.252
[YAWNS]

218
00:13:09.381 --> 00:13:10.575
SHAGGY:
Hey, Scoob.

219
00:13:10.781 --> 00:13:15.536
- How was the first dog day of summer?
- Relaxing.

220
00:13:15.741 --> 00:13:18.380
Glad to hear it, boy.
Now, come on, let's go get some...

221
00:13:18.541 --> 00:13:21.613
Oh, hello, Velma.

222
00:13:21.821 --> 00:13:24.858
- How was your day?
- Fine, I guess.

223
00:13:25.021 --> 00:13:28.172
Oh, really? Like, mine was fine too.

224
00:13:28.341 --> 00:13:30.775
It's crazy
how much we have in common, huh?

225
00:13:31.301 --> 00:13:32.370
Oh, boy.

226
00:13:32.541 --> 00:13:35.578
So, guys, my uncle invited us
to the opening night reception.

227
00:13:35.741 --> 00:13:37.811
- What do you say?
- Awesome.

228
00:13:37.981 --> 00:13:40.256
- How about a dip in the pool first?
DAPHNE: Sounds great.

229
00:13:42.501 --> 00:13:46.210
Oh, like, that sounds like a real rager.
What do you think, V?

230
00:13:46.421 --> 00:13:49.140
Perhaps I'll rendezvous
with everyone later.

231
00:13:49.341 --> 00:13:53.653
Since we arrived, I've been eager
to survey the indigenous flora and fauna.

232
00:13:54.421 --> 00:13:56.377
Oh, hey. Wait up.

233
00:13:56.541 --> 00:14:00.056
So you say there's both flora and fauna
out there, huh?

234
00:14:00.221 --> 00:14:03.975
When was the last time you heard
those two things in the same sentence?

235
00:14:05.341 --> 00:14:06.330
[BELCHES]

236
00:14:07.301 --> 00:14:11.214
Shaggy, did you know
Lake Erie is the warmest...

237
00:14:11.421 --> 00:14:14.652
...and most biologically productive
of the Great Lakes?

238
00:14:14.821 --> 00:14:18.291
Not to mention
the eleventh largest lake in the world.

239
00:14:18.461 --> 00:14:19.450
[METAL DETECTOR BEEPING]

240
00:14:19.621 --> 00:14:20.940
SHAGGY:
Oh, wow.

241
00:14:21.461 --> 00:14:24.737
I could listen to you talk like that
for hours.

242
00:14:25.781 --> 00:14:28.295
Are you really interested
in this stuff, Shaggy?

243
00:14:29.221 --> 00:14:34.090
I've never known you to be,
well, intellectually curious.

244
00:14:35.661 --> 00:14:38.050
Oh, I'm curious
about a lot of things, Velma.

245
00:14:38.261 --> 00:14:39.489
Like...

246
00:14:39.661 --> 00:14:42.129
Like people and relationships...

247
00:14:42.301 --> 00:14:45.657
...and relationships between people.

248
00:14:50.141 --> 00:14:51.938
Hey.

249
00:14:53.421 --> 00:14:55.013
[GRUNTING]

250
00:14:55.941 --> 00:14:59.490
Hey, Shaggy,
you're gonna love this factoid.

251
00:15:00.021 --> 00:15:03.696
Lake Erie has been gradually rising
over the last few hundred years.

252
00:15:03.901 --> 00:15:07.780
That means beneath
all of these rock formations...

253
00:15:07.941 --> 00:15:10.250
...there are miles
of underwater caves.

254
00:15:10.461 --> 00:15:12.975
- Get out of town.
- No, really.

255
00:15:13.141 --> 00:15:15.814
You can tell
by the variegated sedimentary striations.

256
00:15:16.421 --> 00:15:18.571
Oh, would you look at that.

257
00:15:18.741 --> 00:15:23.531
I've never seen irrigated rudimentary
claymations like that before.

258
00:15:24.581 --> 00:15:29.530
Hey, Velma, yesterday at the van...

259
00:15:29.861 --> 00:15:31.055
Uh...

260
00:15:31.221 --> 00:15:32.654
Jinkies.

261
00:15:33.181 --> 00:15:35.854
Look at this, Shaggy.

262
00:15:36.061 --> 00:15:38.939
I think it might actually
be a moonstone.

263
00:15:39.101 --> 00:15:40.739
They're very rare.

264
00:15:40.941 --> 00:15:42.852
You know,
the Native Americans believed...

265
00:15:43.021 --> 00:15:47.458
...they held this mystical connection
with the moon, thereby the name.

266
00:15:49.341 --> 00:15:51.650
Look at how it glows.

267
00:15:52.421 --> 00:15:54.935
It's beautiful, isn't it?

268
00:15:56.541 --> 00:15:58.418
It sure is.

269
00:15:58.581 --> 00:16:01.095
Almost as beautiful as your eyes.

270
00:16:02.581 --> 00:16:05.812
- Oh, Shaggy.
- Oh, Velma.

271
00:16:05.981 --> 00:16:08.973
Oh, Shaggy, I think I'm gonna be sick.

272
00:16:09.141 --> 00:16:13.339
- What? Oh, Velma, are you all right?
- I'm fine.

273
00:16:13.741 --> 00:16:15.936
I just feel really nauseous
all of a sudden.

274
00:16:16.141 --> 00:16:17.859
SHAGGY:
Like, you better sit down.

275
00:16:18.061 --> 00:16:19.972
- Here, let me help.
- No, it's okay.

276
00:16:20.341 --> 00:16:24.016
I'm just gonna go back to the room
and lie down for a little while.

277
00:16:25.261 --> 00:16:27.331
Oh, okay.

278
00:16:34.821 --> 00:16:37.051
I think she likes me.

279
00:16:37.301 --> 00:16:39.337
Oy vay.

280
00:16:42.141 --> 00:16:44.132
[PIANO PLAYING]

281
00:16:44.341 --> 00:16:47.219
THORNY: Well, I'll catch you out there
on the links, huh?

282
00:16:47.381 --> 00:16:48.575
Oh.

283
00:16:48.741 --> 00:16:52.017
Senator. I'm so glad
you could make it.

284
00:16:52.181 --> 00:16:57.050
Oh, how could I ever say no
to my biggest contributor?

285
00:16:57.221 --> 00:16:58.700
- How about a photograph?
- Yes.

286
00:17:02.541 --> 00:17:05.897
- Good thing I dressed up, hey, Scoob?
SCOOBY: Yeah.

287
00:17:06.061 --> 00:17:08.939
Hey, Shagg, Scoob. Where's Velma?

288
00:17:09.101 --> 00:17:10.454
Oh. Uh, heh.

289
00:17:10.621 --> 00:17:14.694
Uh, she got sick all of a sudden.
But it was totally natural causes...

290
00:17:14.861 --> 00:17:17.011
...and not revulsion
at the very thought of me.

291
00:17:17.941 --> 00:17:19.010
Okay.

292
00:17:22.501 --> 00:17:26.255
- Hey, Scoob, check out the buffet.
- Ooh.

293
00:17:27.181 --> 00:17:30.491
Now, if you don't mind,
one from my best side.

294
00:17:31.701 --> 00:17:32.895
One more.

295
00:17:37.581 --> 00:17:40.095
This will be good in my scrapbook.

296
00:17:41.181 --> 00:17:42.853
Perfect.

297
00:17:58.301 --> 00:18:00.656
Like, who ordered the pea soup?

298
00:18:08.981 --> 00:18:10.699
THORNY:
Sorry, everyone.

299
00:18:10.901 --> 00:18:14.177
I'm sure it's just a little minor glitch
with one of our generators.

300
00:18:14.341 --> 00:18:15.535
I'll just...

301
00:18:16.221 --> 00:18:17.210
[GROWLING]

302
00:18:17.381 --> 00:18:19.019
What the heck is that?

303
00:18:19.221 --> 00:18:21.212
[GASPING]

304
00:18:23.901 --> 00:18:26.369
- Fred?
- I don't know either, Daph.

305
00:18:31.981 --> 00:18:33.096
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

306
00:18:33.261 --> 00:18:34.694
[ROARING]

307
00:18:34.861 --> 00:18:38.012
SCOOBY:
Lake monster.

308
00:18:39.741 --> 00:18:43.017
Excuse me, I don't recall
having seen your name on the guest list.

309
00:18:53.781 --> 00:18:55.692
[SCREAMING]

310
00:19:01.301 --> 00:19:02.620
[PHOTOGRAPHER SCREAMS]

311
00:19:06.181 --> 00:19:08.331
That thing can't be real, can it?

312
00:19:08.501 --> 00:19:12.050
I don't know, but I'm not
getting close enough to find out.

313
00:19:13.061 --> 00:19:14.096
Hi.

314
00:19:16.701 --> 00:19:18.419
[ROARS]

315
00:19:24.861 --> 00:19:25.850
THORNY:
No, please.

316
00:19:26.021 --> 00:19:27.010
Please, everyone...

317
00:19:27.181 --> 00:19:30.173
...I'm sure there's a logical explanation
as to what's going on.

318
00:19:30.341 --> 00:19:31.740
We'll just tidy up the tent...

319
00:19:31.901 --> 00:19:35.018
...and, you know,
we'll just continue the party.

320
00:19:35.181 --> 00:19:36.660
Everyone... Oh, senator, senator.

321
00:19:36.821 --> 00:19:39.938
MAN: Give me the keys, I'll get it myself.
WOMAN: Just go without him.

322
00:19:40.421 --> 00:19:41.649
My goodness.

323
00:19:42.381 --> 00:19:45.930
Why do I have the feeling
I missed something rather significant?

324
00:19:46.101 --> 00:19:49.332
It was the lake monster.
The lake monster of Erie Pointe.

325
00:19:49.541 --> 00:19:53.773
It was horrifying, terrifying,
scariest thing I've ever seen in my life.

326
00:19:53.941 --> 00:19:57.138
On a more personal note,
how are you feeling, Velma?

327
00:19:57.301 --> 00:20:00.611
- Did you just say the lake monster?
- Yeah.

328
00:20:00.781 --> 00:20:01.816
You can't be serious.

329
00:20:01.981 --> 00:20:04.939
Oh, my guests sure seemed to think
it was serious.

330
00:20:05.101 --> 00:20:06.659
Look at this, not even day one...

331
00:20:06.821 --> 00:20:09.210
...and half of them
have canceled their memberships.

332
00:20:09.381 --> 00:20:12.339
If somebody doesn't figure out
what's going on here quickly...

333
00:20:12.501 --> 00:20:15.174
...it's gonna be a very short summer
for all of us.

334
00:20:16.221 --> 00:20:18.940
Guys, we have to do something.

335
00:20:19.101 --> 00:20:22.138
We can't afford to lose these jobs.

336
00:20:30.341 --> 00:20:31.330
Oh, no.

337
00:20:31.501 --> 00:20:32.775
No, no, no.

338
00:20:32.941 --> 00:20:34.897
- You guys thinking what I'm thinking?
- No.

339
00:20:35.061 --> 00:20:36.892
- Come on.
- Guys, please, don't...

340
00:20:37.261 --> 00:20:38.250
[SIGHS]

341
00:20:38.421 --> 00:20:40.218
Here we go again.

342
00:20:40.421 --> 00:20:42.139
Uncle Thorny.

343
00:20:43.501 --> 00:20:46.015
We just wanna let you know
not to worry.

344
00:20:46.181 --> 00:20:47.853
Not only did you hire summer help...

345
00:20:48.021 --> 00:20:52.060
...you also hired the best supernatural
detectives in the tristate area.

346
00:20:52.261 --> 00:20:54.252
- I did?
- That's right.

347
00:20:54.421 --> 00:20:56.537
And I know just where to start too.

348
00:20:56.701 --> 00:20:58.896
With Elmer Uggins,
the person who's taken...

349
00:20:59.061 --> 00:21:01.621
...the only known photo
of the lake monster.

350
00:21:16.301 --> 00:21:18.656
FRED:
Heh. Would you look at that.

351
00:21:18.821 --> 00:21:22.575
Our first suspect just happens to be
the keeper of a creepy old lighthouse.

352
00:21:22.781 --> 00:21:24.339
You know, just once...

353
00:21:24.501 --> 00:21:29.097
...I wish we found a mystery
that started in a cheery futon showroom.

354
00:21:29.781 --> 00:21:30.975
What?

355
00:21:31.141 --> 00:21:35.134
Futons offer far more support
than traditional mattresses.

356
00:21:41.061 --> 00:21:43.052
[FOGHORN BLOWS]

357
00:21:55.421 --> 00:21:58.379
Well, looks like the light's on
but nobody's home.

358
00:21:58.541 --> 00:22:01.613
Isn't this the part when we normally
split up and search for clues?

359
00:22:01.781 --> 00:22:03.692
I'll go with Velma. Ha.

360
00:22:05.221 --> 00:22:07.052
Come on. It'll be fun.

361
00:22:07.941 --> 00:22:10.978
Okay. Come on, Daph.

362
00:22:17.781 --> 00:22:19.373
[SHAGGY SNIFFING]

363
00:22:19.541 --> 00:22:24.171
Oh, Velma, what is that sweet fragrance
you're wearing?

364
00:22:24.621 --> 00:22:26.259
Bug and tick repellent.

365
00:22:26.421 --> 00:22:27.570
[MOSQUITO BUZZING]

366
00:22:27.741 --> 00:22:31.017
Well, it certainly isn't repelling me.

367
00:22:36.021 --> 00:22:37.420
[CLEARS THROAT]

368
00:22:38.861 --> 00:22:41.534
It sure is a lovely night, huh?

369
00:22:41.701 --> 00:22:44.534
I've always enjoyed
strolling beneath a full moon.

370
00:22:44.701 --> 00:22:47.693
Werewolves notwithstanding,
of course.

371
00:22:48.101 --> 00:22:51.980
I too enjoy walking
by the light of the silvery moon.

372
00:22:52.141 --> 00:22:53.210
[CHUCKLES]

373
00:22:53.381 --> 00:22:56.657
Heh, heh, heh.
Yeah, that's a good one.

374
00:22:56.821 --> 00:22:58.413
Wait, where's the funny?

375
00:22:59.061 --> 00:23:01.655
- Oh. "By the Light of the Silvery Moon"?
- Yeah.

376
00:23:01.821 --> 00:23:04.540
It's just an old vaudevillian ditty.

377
00:23:04.741 --> 00:23:08.336
But I must confess,
I do have a soft spot for it.

378
00:23:10.701 --> 00:23:14.899
Like, wait, I think I do know that one.

379
